[[File:Bras<U+00E3>odeVascoCoutinho.gif|thumb|Coat of Arms of Vasco Coutinho]]
'''Vasco Fernandes Coutinho''' (1490<U+2013>1561) was the founder of the [[Brazil]]ian state of [[Esp<U+00ED>rito Santo]].

He was born in [[Portugal]]. He was later amongst the first 12 volunteers from Portugal to come to the newly discovered land which came to be known as [[Brazil]]. He was presented the area which became Esp<U+00ED>rito Santo and administered the colony for 25 years, despite being a military man by trade.

He founded the current capital [[Vit<U+00F3>ria, Brazil|Vit<U+00F3>ria]] and the first capital, today known as [[Vila Velha]] ("Old Town").

During his administration Esp<U+00ED>rito Santo's first two churches <U+2013> S<U+00E3>o Jo<U+00E3>o and Ros<U+00E1>rio founded in 1551, both in Vila Velha <U+2013> were founded. Both are still standing.

